\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Flux Shape for Adjoint and Forward Fluxes using Two Group Diffusion Theory
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
For the perturbations of thermal absorption cross section by 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\%$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $5\%$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

, estimate the reactivity change using the first order perturbation theory
 formula.
 Also determine the exact reactivity change by calculating the multiplication
 factors of the base and perturbed cases and compare the results with those
 of FOP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are assuming this is a one group point model, and thus we can use the
 first order perturbation equation given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\rho=-\Delta\lambda=\frac{\left\langle \phi^{*},\left[\lambda\mathbf{F}^{'}-\mathbf{M^{'}}\right]\phi\right\rangle }{\left\langle \phi^{*},\mathbf{F}\phi\right\rangle }=\frac{\Delta\left(\nu\Sigma_{f}\right)-\nu\Sigma_{f}\Delta\Sigma_{a}}{\left(\nu\Sigma_{f}\right)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the fission cross section or yield has not changed (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu\Sigma_{f}=0$
\end_inset

), we can find out the change in reactivity by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\rho=\frac{\nu\Sigma_{f}\Delta\Sigma_{a}}{\left(\nu\Sigma_{f}\right)^{2}}=\frac{\Delta\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the reactivity changes by for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\%$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $5\%$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 change in absorption cross section by that amount over the fission cross
 section times the fission yield.
 Given the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\Sigma_{f}$
\end_inset

, we could then calculate the reactivity differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exact difference is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\rho_{e}=\frac{\Delta\left(\nu\Sigma_{f}\right)\Sigma_{a}-\nu\Sigma_{f}\Delta\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}\left[\nu\Sigma_{f}+\Delta\left(\nu\Sigma_{f}\right)\right]}=\frac{\Delta\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
showing no change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also determine the change in multiplication factor using the one
 group point formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ott1989"

\end_inset

.
 For one group,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=\frac{\nu\Sigma_{f}}{DB^{2}+\Sigma_{a}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho=1-\frac{1}{k}=1-\frac{DB^{2}+\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}=\frac{\nu\Sigma_{f}-DB^{2}-\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now if we perturb 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{a}^{'}=\Sigma_{a}+\delta\Sigma_{a}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k^{'}=\frac{\nu\Sigma_{f}}{DB^{2}+\Sigma_{a}+\delta\Sigma_{a}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho^{'}=1-\frac{1}{k^{'}}=1-\frac{DB^{2}+\Sigma_{a}+\delta\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}=\frac{\nu\Sigma_{f}-DB^{2}-\Sigma_{a}-\delta\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{'}=\rho+\delta\rho$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\rho=\rho^{'}-\rho=\frac{\nu\Sigma_{f}-DB^{2}-\Sigma_{a}-\delta\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}-\frac{\nu\Sigma_{f}-DB^{2}-\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simplifying, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\rho=\frac{\delta\Sigma_{a}}{\nu\Sigma_{f}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result is exactly the same as the first order perturbation theory result,
 and the reactivity will again change by the amount of absorption perturbation
 divided by the fission cross section times the fission yield.
\end_layout

